	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">kevtris wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I figure this is the best shot I have at making some kind of "FPGA thing" to sell.  The hard part about it is the FPGA alone costs $42 on it, and there's not much I can do about getting that lowered.  There might be a quantity discount but there doesn't seem to be.</div>
<br />I've been planning on producing some form of commercial FPGA-based retro product for the past 5 years. But my ambitions always outstrip the current technology / price-point trade-off that would make it commercially viable. Hence the reason I have nothing at all to show for years of "tinkering" except a bunch of relatively simple projects.
<br />
<br />If you're considering a SNES, I'd humbly suggest you not worry about the hardware at all for now and start developing on the most powerful hardware you can lay your hands on. For one, it'll make your development job easier. And two, by the time it's ready technology will be cheaper; you can always sit on it for a bit if not. A good design will be relatively portable across hardware targets.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


