	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">65024U wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Not to be mean but Cloud9 and Coco3 have Cf card devices, serial connections from PC-&gt;Coco, Hard drive and CF IDE-like environments and much more. Not that you doing it is a waste, it just already exists and since we have the SuperIDE with the flash card slot, too, I will say it's awesome.</div>
<br />I'm well versed in the Coco scene and all the products that are available.
<br />
<br />I'm not looking to produce a product that connects to a real Coco. I'm developing an all-in-one FPGA emulation that actually emulates some of those Cloud9 products on-chip. For instance, I already emulate the SuperIDE controller, with full HDBDOS support via CF. I'm just looking to (also) use the SD card as an IDE peripheral, to use on the DE1 for example.
<br />
<br />I have also had Drivewire running on the emulation, but only when using an external 6809. There is no cycle-accurate 6809 core available (yet), so the hand-crafted bit-bash routines in Drivewire won't quite work. Gary Becker got around that on his Coco3FPGA emulation by (IIUC) re-coding parts of the routines. As far as I'm concerned, that's cheating. I want to be able to use the "original" software.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


